{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Seam-map: module/interface seam (file discovery + filename parsing + execution ordering). A unit test of only the sort helper can miss real failures in runner wiring (e.g., discovered list ordering, async iteration, or filtering before apply). REAL-INFRA/LLM/MULTI-STEP do not apply.","test_description":"Create a temp migrations directory with out-of-order files (e.g., 001.sql, 010.sql, 002.sql). Run the migration runner against a test DB/repo adapter that records execution order. Assert apply order is 001, 002, 010 and metadata rows follow that order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Seam-map: module/interface seam between migration runner and _migrations state persistence across runs. Needs two runner invocations sharing DB state; single-function unit tests are insufficient. Rejected System: behavior text is about persisted state/idempotency, not OS/network/subprocess-specific failure.","test_description":"Run runner once with a migration that mutates schema/data and records in _migrations. Run runner again on same DB. Assert migration body side effect occurs only once and no duplicate _migrations record is inserted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Seam-map: module/interface seam at transaction handling + runner control flow (rollback + stop). Must exercise real transaction behavior with runner orchestration; a mocked transaction can hide failures. Rejected System: no required OS/network/subprocess boundary in behavior text beyond DB transaction semantics that can be covered in integration with local DB wiring.","test_description":"Use migrations where one file performs a write then triggers SQL error, followed by another valid migration. Run runner. Assert failed migration leaves no partial writes (rolled back), later migration is not applied, and _migrations only includes prior successful versions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Seam-map: environment seam (real concurrent separate processes + shared DB locking/constraints). Behavior explicitly requires separate processes; in-process mocks can miss race conditions and lock timing. Higher levels (Agentic/Workflow) are disqualified: no AI/ML output or multi-agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Launch two runner processes simultaneously against the same test PostgreSQL DB with overlapping migration set. Wait for both to finish. Assert each migration effect exists exactly once and _migrations contains one row per version with no duplicates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.87,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Seam-map: module/interface seam between bootstrap metadata initialization and migration application flow. Needs runner + DB schema interaction; unit tests of helper methods can miss ordering bug in orchestration. Rejected System: behavior does not require subprocess/OS/network-specific effects.","test_description":"Start with fresh DB lacking _migrations. Run runner with at least one migration that would fail if _migrations bootstrap ordering were wrong. Assert _migrations table exists and first migration is applied only after table creation path succeeds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
